268
news & views
AGING
Impaired gut barrier affects microglia health
As researchers uncover new roles for the microbiome in health and disease, recent studies have emerged linking 
the microbiome to aspects of aging. Mossad and colleagues demonstrate that a microbiome-mediated disruption 
of the intestinal barrier, associated with aging, can contribute to dysfunction of microglia in mice.
John W. Bostick and Sarkis K. Mazmanian
A
s human lifespan increases, 
age-related diseases will impose 
greater burdens on societies and 
economies around the world. Yet, many 
aspects of the aging process remain poorly 
understood, including how environmental 
and lifestyle factors influence aging. 
Research into the effect of gut bacteria 
on health and disease has become an 
area of recent interest, as seminal studies 
have shown a role for the microbiome in 
age-related conditions such as Alzheimer’s 
disease and Parkinson’s disease1,2, as well  
as on cellular and molecular signatures  
of aging and cognition3,4. However, it 
remains unclear whether aging-related 
changes to the gut microbiome and 
microglia are linked.
A new study by Mossad et al.5 in  
Nature Neuroscience demonstrates  
that microbiome-mediated changes in 
intestinal permeability during aging may 
promote translocation of gut-derived 
metabolites into the circulation, and  
possibly the brain. These metabolites in  
turn may alter microglial function 
and shift them into a pathogenic 
state5 (Fig. 1). Specifically, to explore 
microbiome-influenced effects on 
microglial dysfunction in aging, Mossad 
and colleagues5 examined differences in 
the gene expression by microglia from 
young (6–10 weeks old) and aged (96–104 
weeks old) mice under germ-free (GF) 
or specific-pathogen-free (SPF) housing 
conditions. By comparing GF mice  
(which lack a microbiome) to SPF mice, the 
authors could ascribe observed differences 
in microglial function to gut bacteria, 
although this research approach does 
not impute any functions to individual 
microorganisms. The authors report that 
microglia from both GF and SPF mice 
display an age-dependent transcriptomic 
signature, as measured by RNA sequencing. 
However, the magnitude of differences 
in age-related gene expression was more 
pronounced in microglia from SPF mice 
compared to their GF counterparts.  
Notably, the greatest differences in gene 
expression were found in comparisons  
of aged SPF and GF mice, including  
changes in genes involved in cytoskeleton, 
immune function and mitochondrial 
regulation. Mitochondria are critical  
cellular components in energy production 
processes and have an important role in 
cellular aging by modulating the production 
of reactive oxygen species (ROS) and 
oxidative stress responses. The striking 
changes in gene expression relating to 
mitochondrial function prompted the 
authors to investigate microbiome-driven 
effects on mitochondria.
A detailed look at the genes involved in 
ROS production revealed an upregulation 
of ROS-promoting genes and ROS-response 
genes only in microglia from aged SPF  
mice, indicating ROS levels in microglia  
are regulated by both aging and the  
presence of microbiota. Indeed, ROS 
concentrations were elevated in microglia 
from SPF mice upon aging, compared  
to the lower levels in GF mice. In addition,  
the authors found evidence that 
mitochondria were damaged and 
dysfunctional (with decreased ATP 
production) in microglia from aged  
SPF mice, indicating that a replete 
microbiota contributes to microglia  
function in aged mice. Although 
comparisons with mice that have no  
gut bacteria lead to simple binary outcomes 
that are not natural (that is, there are  
no GF animals or humans in nature), 
this approach set the stage to ask how 
microorganisms in the intestines affect 
mitochondrial function within microglia.
