Fig. 1 | Increased intestinal permeability with age facilitates the translocation and accumulation 
of metabolites that promote microglia dysfunction. Increased barrier permeability driven by the 
gut microbiome and associated with aging leads to increased translocation of metabolites into the 
circulation and brain (for example, N(6)-carboxymethyllysine (CML)). CML accumulates in the brain 
and may contribute to mitochondrial damage and dysfunction in microglia as mice age (top right).
