269
news & views
Gut microbial species contain a  
diverse array of biosynthetic pathways 
to metabolize many classes of dietary 
compounds into small- and large-molecule 
metabolites that may influence host 
functions, including short-chain fatty  
acids (SCFAs) that modulate energy 
metabolism in intestinal epithelial cells 
and regulate several facets of the immune 
system6. A portion of these molecules  
enter circulation and may reach the  
brain, and studies have shown that the 
microbiome and its associated metabolites 
(such as SCFAs) can influence pathology 
in mouse models of Alzheimer’s disease 
or Parkinson’s disease1,2,7. Mossad and 
co-workers5 used targeted and untargeted 
metabolomics to examine a range of 
metabolites in the serum and brain that 
were altered with age. Several metabolites 
were significantly upregulated in both 
serum and brains of aged mice, including 
acetate, propionate, palmitoleate (16:1n7), 
trimethylamine N-oxide (TMAO), 
1-oleoyl-2-242 docosahexaenoyl-GPC 
(18:1/22:6), stachydrine and 
N(6)-carboxymethyllysine (CML). Two 
metabolites (TMAO and CML) were also 
found by non-targeted metabolomics to 
increase in human blood samples with age. 
SCFAs, such as acetate and propionate, 
are generated from dietary fiber by the 
microbiota and can influence microglial 
activation in the mouse brain2. TMAO  
is generated through the metabolism 
and oxidation of dietary amines by 
microorganisms in the gut and subsequent 
enzymatic reactions in the liver, and has 
previously been shown to negatively 
influence disease outcomes in rodent  
models of stroke8. CML is a member of 
a molecular class known as advanced 
glycation end products, which are generated 
through the oxidation and glycation 
reactions (for example, Maillard reaction)  
of proteins. Advanced glycation end 
products are associated with stress responses 
and have previously been proposed to  
be involved in the pathogenesis of 
Alzheimer’s disease9, although more  
work is needed to replicate initial 
observations and implicate potential 
functional outcomes for these metabolites.
In proof-of-concept studies, acetate, 
propionate, TMAO and CML were 
experimentally elevated in young mice  
by intraperitoneal injection, which  
facilitates distribution directly into the 
circulation. Of the four metabolites 
tested, only CML partially recapitulated 
the increased oxidative stress, decreased 
mitochondrial function and structural 
damage to mitochondria that were  
observed in microglia from the brains 
of aged mice. This led the researchers to 
investigate the source of increased CML in 
the brain, and they initially hypothesized — 
appropriately — that the increase in CML 
in the brain may be microbiota-dependent. 
Strikingly, GF mice had higher levels of 
CML in feces than did SPF mice, revealing 
that microbial metabolism is not the source 
of increased CML.
The intestinal epithelium serves as a 
firewall between animals and their gut 
bacteria, and previous studies have shown 
that the microbiome is a key regulator  
of intestinal permeability, a barrier 
dysfunction that can modulate systemic 
levels of gut-derived metabolites10.  
The authors assessed intestinal permeability 
by measuring translocation of a  
fluorescently labeled molecule from  
the gut to the circulation after oral 
delivery. They found that aged SPF mice 
had increased intestinal permeability, 
which was not observed in aged GF mice. 
Moreover, young GF mice colonized 
with microorganisms by fecal transfer 
from aged mice showed higher levels of 
leakage by the fluorescent tracer out of the 
gut, as compared to young GF mice with 
microorganisms from young donor mice. 
These observations are best explained by 
age-dependent changes to the microbiome 
that alter CML translocation rather than 
metabolite levels directly, with the net  
effect of increased CML in the circulation 
and brains of mice (at least in this 
experimental system). It remains unknown 
how aging changes microbiome effects  
on gut permeability.
Accordingly, the authors examined 
how the route of CML delivery affects its 
accumulation in microglia. For young 
SPF mice, increased CML was observed 
in microglia only after intraperitoneal 
injection, compared to low levels after 
oral delivery. By contrast, aged SPF mice 
displayed increased CML accumulation 
following both systemic and oral 
administration of the metabolite, indicating 
that increased intestinal permeability  
may allow CML to more readily translocate 
out of the gut and reach the brain. Finally,  
to test whether intestinal permeability  
affects peripheral and central CML 
levels, the authors treated mice orally 
with molecules that either prevent the 
accumulation of CML (ellagic acid) 
or enhance intestinal barrier function 
(intestinal alkaline phosphatase)11,12. Both 
treatments decreased CML accumulation  
in the brain. Although ellagic acid had 
no effect on intestinal permeability, the 
treatment reduced CML build-up in the 
brain, indicating that the intestine is a 
key source of the metabolite. Increasing 
gut barrier function with intestinal 
alkaline phosphatase demonstrated that a 
gut-to-circulation route appears to influence 
age-associated accumulation of CML  
in the brain.
Mossad and colleagues5 have identified 
an important microbiota-driven  
process in aging, in which potentially 
pathogenic gut molecules appear to 
influence cellular responses in the  
brains of mice. Many questions remain 
unresolved; for example, how CML alters 
microglial function and whether its  
effects on these cells are direct or via  
other cells; whether there are other 
gut-derived metabolites with redundant, 
synergistic or antagonistic functions; 
and how an aged microbiota promotes 
intestinal permeability, and whether this 
process can be reversed (perhaps with 
fecal transplants from young mice or with 
probiotics). Reciprocal actions of the aging 
host and microbiome may contribute to 
intestinal permeability. Intestinal barrier 
function is mediated by physical, chemical 
and cellular components, including the 
intestinal epithelium, mucus layer, secreted 
molecules and immune cells. Dysfunction 
in any of the critical components of barrier 
function may lead to increased intestinal 
permeability. Evidence demonstrates that 
these components are regulated by gut 
microorganisms; however, the influence of 
aging has only recently been investigated. 
Future studies are needed to identify the 
cellular and molecular changes associated 
with aging that may alter intestinal  
barrier function.
If these results are replicated and 
extended to humans, they may represent 
new perspectives for how aging and the 
environment can affect brain function,  
and potentially age-related disorders  
and behaviors. Increased intestinal 
permeability, or ‘leaky gut’, has been 
associated with several neurological 
conditions (including Alzheimer’s disease, 
Parkinson’s disease, depression and 
autism spectrum disorder), although a 
contributing role has not been validated. 
Further, accumulation of other neuroactive 
gut-derived metabolites in the brains of mice 
has recently been reported. Collectively, 
emerging evidence appears to suggest that 
certain brain functions may be influenced  
by molecules from diet, microorganisms  
and/or host–microbial co-metabolism,  
with examples of both protective (for 
example, SCFA) and pathogenic  
(for example, CML) metabolites. Ensuring 
intestinal barrier integrity to regulate the 
translocation of metabolites from the  
gut may represent a new approach to 
promoting brain health.
