DECISION-MAKING
Closing the loop on models of interval timing
A study by Cook et al. shows that mice can use auditory feedback from their own actions to precisely time 
an interval. This feedback is processed in the secondary auditory cortex and regulates performance via a 
corticostriatal circuit.
Konstantin I. Bakhurin and Henry H. Yin
A
daptive behavior is characterized 
by its goal (why), its means (what), 
its action parameters (how) and 
its timing (when). Of these, the question 
of when poses a unique challenge to the 
organism. The timing of behavior requires 
the ability to anticipate the time of future 
events on the basis of past experience 
and to adjust behavioral performance 
accordingly. This ability, known as interval 
timing, requires great flexibility. Intervals 
could begin at any time, and must be 
reset as needed according to changes in 
environmental contingencies (for example, 
when rewards become available). Unlike 
circadian systems that rely on biological 
oscillators with a regular and genetically 
programmed rhythm, interval timing deals 
with shorter and variable intervals in the 
range of seconds to minutes. There is no 
fixed rhythm, and the relevant intervals 
must be learned and regularly updated.
The classic scalar expectancy model 
of timing posits three components: a 
pacemaker, an accumulator or integrator, 
and a comparator1. The pacemaker generates 
repetitive pulses that are accumulated by the 
integrator, and the comparator compares 
the current output of the integrator with 
a reference value stored in memory; 
performance is regulated by the output of 
the comparator. Studies have suggested that 
corticobasal ganglia circuits are critical for 
interval timing2, but it remains unclear how 
different components of the model may be 
implemented by these circuits.
A study by Cook et al.3 sheds light on 
the neural mechanisms of timing. In a 
series of careful experiments, they provide 
compelling evidence that the brain uses 
sensory feedback from self-initiated actions 
to time short intervals. The authors first 
trained mice to press a lever for food. They 
then imposed a fixed-interval contingency: 
on a given trial, the mouse initiates the timer 
by pressing a lever, and the first press after 
30 s is rewarded. Mice display sustained 
bouts of lever pressing during the interval, 
and terminate the bout after the interval 
has elapsed to collect the food. To assess the 
internal estimation of time, rewards were 
omitted on some probe trials. With training 
on these probe trials, mice learn to terminate 
lever pressing once they decide that the 30-s 
interval has passed, as there is no external 
cue that signals reward.
How do the mice know that 30 s have 
passed? The authors tested whether trained 
mice rely on sensory signals to time the 
interval on this task, by systematically 
depriving them of inputs from different 
sensory modalities — visual, auditory, 
